, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form, <i>Io(h)anna</i>, of Greek <i>Iōanna</i>, the feminine equivalent of <i>Iōannēs</i> (  see  John  ). In the New Testament, this name is borne by a woman who was one of Jesus's followers (Luke 8:3; 24:10). She was the wife of the steward of the household of King Herod Antipas. The name was regularly used throughout the Middle Ages in most parts of Europe as a feminine equivalent of   John  , but in England it has only been in common use as a vernacular given name since the 19th century. Celebrated British bearers of the name include the novelist  Joanna Trollope  (  b. 1943 ), the actress  Joanna Lumley  (  b. 1946 ), and the concert pianist  Joanna McGregor  (  b. 1959 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Joannah","meanings":["From the Latin form, <i>Io(h)anna</i>, of Greek <i>Iōanna</i>, the feminine equivalent of <i>Iōannēs</i> (  see  John  ). In the New Testament, this name is borne by a woman who was one of Jesus's followers (Luke 8:3; 24:10). She was the wife of the steward of the household of King Herod Antipas. The name was regularly used throughout the Middle Ages in most parts of Europe as a feminine equivalent of   John  , but in England it has only been in common use as a vernacular given name since the 19th century. Celebrated British bearers of the name include the novelist  Joanna Trollope  (  b. 1943 ), the actress  Joanna Lumley  (  b. 1946 ), and the concert pianist  Joanna McGregor  (  b. 1959 )."]},{"name":"Joana","meanings":["From the Latin form, <i>Io(h)anna</i>, of Greek <i>Iōanna</i>, the feminine equivalent of <i>Iōannēs</i> (  see  John  ). In the New Testament, this name is borne by a woman who was one of Jesus's followers (Luke 8:3; 24:10). She was the wife of the steward of the household of King Herod Antipas. The name was regularly used throughout the Middle Ages in most parts of Europe as a feminine equivalent of   John  , but in England it has only been in common use as a vernacular given name since the 19th century. Celebrated British bearers of the name include the novelist  Joanna Trollope  (  b. 1943 ), the actress  Joanna Lumley  (  b. 1946 ), and the concert pianist  Joanna McGregor  (  b. 1959 )."]}]},{"name":"verch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Orlo.","German: variant of   Ferch  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferch","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."]}]},{"name":"Rhys","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name meaning ‘ardour’; borne in the Middle Ages by various rulers in south-west Wales, including  Rhys ap Tewdur  (  d. 1093 ) and  Rhys ap Gruffudd  (  1132–97 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Reece","meanings":["Anglicized spelling of Rhys . The name is now in widespread and frequent use outside Wales, in many cases representing a transferred use of the surname so spelled, which is derived from the given name."]},{"name":"Rees","meanings":["Anglicized spelling of Welsh Rhys, in some cases representing a transferred use of the surname so spelled, which is derived from the Welsh given name."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"STACKPOLE","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Welsh: habitational name from Stackpole (Pembrokeshire), apparently named with Old Norse <i>stakkr</i> ‘stack’ + <i>pollr</i> ‘pool’, referring to a stack of rocks on the coast at the entrance to Broadhaven. The name was taken to Ireland and adapted by settlers of Norman descent, where it is recorded in Dublin as early as 1200. The name has been Gaelicized as <b>de Stacapúl</b>; the family was also known in Irish as <b>Galldubh</b> ‘dark stranger’."],"variants":[{"name":"Stackpoole","meanings":["English (Cheshire) and Welsh: variant of   Stackpole  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Joanna verch Rhys Heiress of STACKPOLE was born in 1369, in Haddon Hall, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Rhys Griffith II and Isabel de Stackpole. She married Lord Richard VI Vernon van Haddon in 1388, in Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1412, in Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 43."},"et":{"1369–1412":"1369–1412","1362–1403":"1362–1403","1376–Male":"1376–Surnud","1390–Male":"1390–Surnud","1423–1474":"1423–1474","–Male":"Surnud","–1432":"–1432","1325–1380":"1325–1380","–Female":"Surnud","1362":"1362","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","1403":"1403","1369":"1369","1325":"1325","1412":"1412","1423":"1423","1388":"1388","1432":"1432","1376":"1376","1474":"1474","23 July 1403":"23. juuli 1403","27 May 1380":"27. mai 1380","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Haddon, Derbyshire, England":"Haddon Hall, Derbyshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England":"Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England"},"fi":{"1369–1412":"1369–1412","1362–1403":"1362–1403","1376–Male":"1376–Kuollut","1390–Male":"1390–Kuollut","1423–1474":"1423–1474","–Male":"Kuollut","–1432":"–1432","1325–1380":"1325–1380","–Female":"Kuollut","1362":"1362","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","1403":"1403","1369":"1369","1325":"1325","1412":"1412","1423":"1423","1388":"1388","1432":"1432","1376":"1376","1474":"1474","23 July 1403":"23. heinäkuuta 1403","27 May 1380":"27. toukokuuta 1380","De